<LessonPage
  title="Lesson 3 · C# static and instance members"
  heading="One type, many objects: <code>static</code> versus instance"
  lede="Today’s win: decide whether a member needs one particular object or belongs to the type itself, then call it through the right receiver."
  backHref="/topics/csharp/"
  backLabel="C# lessons"
>
  <LessonSection title="The ownership question">
    <Callout>
      An instance member belongs to one particular object. A <code>static</code> member belongs to the type. Static does not mean “outside the class.”
    </Callout>
    <p>
      A class describes what its objects contain and can do. Each <code>Workout</code> object has its own name and duration, so those properties and any behavior that uses them are instance members.
    </p>
    <p>
      A static method has no implicit current object—no <code>this</code>. It can still work with values passed as arguments, but you call it through the type name.
    </p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="One small class">
    <p>
      The constructor receives the starting state for each new object. <code>Name</code>, <code>Minutes</code>, and <code>Describe</code> are instance members. <code>IsLong</code> is static because it only needs the number supplied to it.
    </p>
    <Code code={classExample} lang="csharp" />
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Read the receiver before the member">
    <Code code={validCalls} lang="csharp" />
    <ul>
      <li><code>walk.Describe()</code> uses the state in the <code>walk</code> object.</li>
      <li><code>run.Describe()</code> uses the separate state in the <code>run</code> object.</li>
      <li><code>Workout.IsLong(...)</code> calls behavior owned by the type and supplies all required data explicitly.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The dot does not always mean the same ownership. Look to its left: an object such as <code>walk</code> selects one instance; the type name <code>Workout</code> selects a static member.
    </p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Two useful compiler failures" variant="warning">
    <p><code>Workout.Describe()</code> fails because no particular workout was selected. <code>walk.IsLong(20)</code> fails because C# requires a static member to be accessed through its type.</p>
    <p>The smallest repairs are to choose an object for <code>Describe</code> and use <code>Workout</code> for <code>IsLong</code>.</p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Predict and repair" variant="checkpoint">
    <Code code={taskCode} lang="csharp" />
    <ReplyTask id="learn:csharp/003:q1" difficulty={3} copyText={replyText}>
      <p>Without running the code:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Predict the first two output lines.</li>
        <li>Classify the properties, <code>Describe</code>, and <code>IsLong</code> by ownership.</li>
        <li>Repair both invalid calls with the smallest changes.</li>
        <li>Explain why the corrected calls need different receivers.</li>
      </ol>
    </ReplyTask>
  </LessonSection>
</LessonPage>
